r 1177":"efter 1177","Paisley, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Paisley, Renfrewshire, Skotland","Scotland":"Skotland, United Kingdom","Eaglesham, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Eaglesham, Renfrewshire, Skotland"},"nl":{"1144–about 1190":"1144–circa 1190","1144–1190":"1144–1190","–1234":"–1234","1144–1221":"1144–1221","1180–1214":"1180–1214","1190–1260":"1190–1260","1225–1285":"1225–1285","1118–1177":"1118–1177","–Female":"Overleden","1190":"1190","about 1190":"circa 1190","1143":"1143","1285":"1285","1260":"1260","1180":"1180","1118":"1118","1225":"1225","1214":"1214","1234":"1234","1144":"1144","1177":"1177","1221":"1221","after 1177":"na 1177","Paisley, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Paisley, Renfrewshire, Schotland","Scotland":"Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Eaglesham, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Eaglesham, Renfrewshire, Schotland"},"en":{"1144–about 1190":"1144–about 1190","1144–1190":"1144–1190","–1234":"–1234","1144–1221":"1144–1221","1180–1214":"1180–1214","1190–1260":"1190–1260","1225–1285":"1225–1285","1118–1177":"1118–1177","–Female":"Deceased","1190":"1190","about 1190":"about 1190","1143":"1143","1285":"1285","1260":"1260","1180":"1180","1118":"1118","1225":"1225","1214":"1214","1234":"1234","1144":"1144","1177":"1177","1221":"1221","after 1177":"after 1177","Paisley, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Paisley, Renfrewshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland, United Kingdom","Eaglesham, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Eaglesham, Renfrewshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"St","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Americanized spelling of French   St  .   Denis  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Denis","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Camille, Jacques, Armand, Marcel, Andre, Pierre, Serge, Yvan, Alphonse, Edouard, Francois, Gaetane.  Spanish Jose, Carlos, Jorge, Roberto, Angel, Francisco, Joaquin, Juan, Manuel, Miguel, Ramon, Rolando.","French, Walloon, Breton, West Indian (mainly Haiti), German, Dutch, English, and Portuguese; Spanish and Galician (<b>Denís</b>): from the personal name <i>Denis</i>, Spanish and Galician <i>Denís</i>, from Latin <i>Dionysius</i> ‘(follower) of Dionysos’ (see   Dennis  ). Compare   Dennee  .","Ukrainian and Rusyn: variant transliteration of   Denys  , a cognate of 1 above."]}]},{"name":"Martin","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English, Scottish, Irish, French, Walloon, Breton, Dutch, Flemish, German, Czech, Slovak, Croatian, Italian (Veneto); Spanish (<b>Martín</b>): from a personal name derived from Latin <i>Martinus</i>, itself a derivative of <i>Mars</i>, genitive <i>Martis</i>, the Roman god of fertility and war, whose name may derive ultimately from a root <i>mar</i> ‘gleam’. This was borne by a famous 4th-century Christian saint, Martin of Tours, and consequently became extremely popular throughout Europe in the Middle Ages. In North America, the surname <i>Martin</i> has absorbed cognates and derivatives from other languages, e.g. Slovak and Rusyn (from Slovakia)   Marcin  , Albanian   Martini  , Polish surnames beginning with <i>Marcin-</i>, and Slovenian patronymics like <b>Martinčič</b> (see   Martincic  ). <i>Martin</i> is the most frequent surname in France and one of the most frequent surnames in Wallonia.","English: variant of   Marton  .","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Mártain</b>, ‘descendant of Martin’ (compare 1 above). Otherwise, a shortened form of   Gilmartin   or   McMartin  ; sometimes also spelled <i>Martyn</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Marczewski","meanings":["Polish: habitational name for someone from Marcewo (formerly also <i>Marczewo</i>) in Greater Poland Voivodeship. Alternatively, a derivative of the personal name <i>Marc</i>, <i>Marcz</i>, a pet form of <i>Marcin</i>, <i>Marek</i> (see   Martin  ,   Mark  )."]},{"name":"Marciniak","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Eugeniusz, Ewa, Agnieszka, Bartosz, Boleslaw, Ignatius, Jaroslaw, Jerzy, Krystyna, Ryszard, Slawomir, Stanislawa.","Polish: patronymic from the personal name <i>Marcin</i> (see   Martin  )."]},{"name":"Marak","meanings":["Czech:","(<b>Marák</b>): from a pet form of the personal names   Martin   or   Marek  .","(<b>Mařák</b>): metronymic from the female personal name <i>Máří</i>, Czech form of   Maria  . It may also denoted the husband of a woman named <i>Máří</i>."]},{"name":"Machain","meanings":["Basque: Castilianized form of <b>Matxain</b>, a topographic or habitational name referring to a house named with a diminutive of the personal name   Martin  ."]},{"name":"Maertens","meanings":["Flemish and Dutch: patronymic from the personal name <i>Maerten</i>, a variant of   Martin  .","North German (<b>Märtens</b>): see   Martens  ."]},{"name":"Marcin","meanings":["Slovak, Rusyn (from Slovakia), and Polish: from <i>Marcin</i>, a personal name equivalent to   Martin  . In Poland this is the most usual form as a personal name, but the surname is very rare there, while in Slovakia, where <i>Marcin</i> is a dialect form of the name <i>Martin</i>, the situation is opposite.","American shortened form of Polish   Marcinkiewicz   and other derivatives of the personal name <i>Marcin</i> (see 1 above).","In some cases possibly also French: from a vernacular form of the personal name <i>Marcien</i>, derived from the Latin surname <i>Marcianus</i>, popularized through the cult of a local saint."]},{"name":"Macho","meanings":["Spanish: nickname from <i>macho</i> ‘male; mule’ (from Latin <i>masculus</i> ‘male, masculine’), applied either to denote a virile, strong man or alternatively an idiot.","Spanish: possibly also a nickname for a forceful person or a metonymic occupational name for a smith, from <i>macho</i> ‘sledgehammer’ (from Latin <i>marculus</i> ‘hammer’).","Slovak: from a derivative of the personal name   Martin  ."]},{"name":"Marcinowski","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Aleksander, Bogdan, Jerzy, Zbigniew, Zigmund.","Polish: habitational name for someone from any of the places called Marcinów, Marcinowa, Marcinowice, or any of numerous other places in Poland named with the personal name <i>Marcin</i> (see   Martin  )."]},{"name":"Marcinkiewicz","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Henryk, Beata, Elzbieta, Janina.","Polish: patronymic from the personal name <i>Marcinek</i>, a petform of <i>Marcin</i> (see   Martin  )."]},{"name":"Mar","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Gim, Wai, Fong, Hong, Man Chung, Moo, Mun, Quon, Wing, Yat, Bok, Chun.","Spanish, Portuguese, Galician, Asturian-Leonese, and Catalan: topographic name for someone living by the sea, from <i>mar</i> ‘sea’ (from Latin <i>mare</i>).","German: nickname from Middle High German <i>mar(w)</i> ‘tender, delicate’, or an altered form of <b>Mahr</b>, a topographic name from <i>mar</i> ‘lake, swamp, stagnant water’."]}]},{"name":"Mary","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Hebrew.  See  <b>Maria</b>   and   <b>Mary</b> ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Attainment’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mary de St Martin was born in 1144, in Paisley, Renfrewshire, Scotland, United Kingdom as the daughter of Henrico de St. Martin and Beatrice Riche. She married Sir Alan Montgomery x in Eaglesham, Renfrewshire, Scotland. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. She died about 1190, in Scotland, United Kingdom, at the age of 47."},"et":{"1144–about 1190":"1144–umbes 1190","1144–1190":"1144–1190","–1234":"–1234","1144–1221":"1144–1221","1180–1214":"1180–1214","1190–1260":"1190–1260","1225–1285":"1225–1285","1118–1177":"1118–1177","–Female":"Surnud","1190":"1190","about 1190":"umbes 1190","1143":"1143","1285":"1285","1260":"1260","1180":"1180","1118":"1118","1225":"1225","1214":